# TODO: the 30 books published in 2014 with the most ratings
top_books_chart = (
    alt.Chart(book_data)
    .transform_filter("datum.Publishing_Year == 2014")  
    .transform_window(
        rank='rank()',
        sort=[alt.SortField('Book_Ratings_Count', order='descending')] 
    )
    .transform_filter("datum.rank <= 30") 
    .mark_bar()
    .encode(
        x=alt.X('Book_Ratings_Count:Q', title='Book_Ratings_Count'),
        y=alt.Y('Book_Name:N', sort='-x', title='Book_Name'),
        color=alt.Color(
            'Author_Rating:N',
            scale=alt.Scale(
                domain=["Excellent", "Famous", "Intermediate", "Novice"],
                range=['#4c78a8', '#f48518', '#e35756', '#71b7b1']
            ),
            legend=alt.Legend(title="Author_Rating")
        )
    )
    .properties(
        title="30 Most Rated Books of 2014",
        width=420,  
        height=620
    )
    .configure_title(fontWeight="bold")  
    .configure_axis(
        titleFontWeight="bold"  
    )
)

top_books_chart

In[4]:
filtered_books = book_data[
    (book_data["Book_Average_Rating"] >= 4) &
    (book_data["Units_Sold"] > 0) &
    (book_data["Publisher_Revenue"].notnull())
].copy()

filtered_books["Revenue_per_Book"] = filtered_books["Publisher_Revenue"] / filtered_books["Units_Sold"]

revenue_chart = (
    alt.Chart(filtered_books)
    .transform_aggregate(
        avg_revenue='mean(Revenue_per_Book)',  
        groupby=["Publishing_Year", "Author_Rating"]
    )
    .mark_line()
    .encode(
        x=alt.X("Publishing_Year:O", 
                title="Publishing_Year",
                axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),  
        y=alt.Y("avg_revenue:Q", 
                title="Average Revenue per Book Sold",
                axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),  
        color=alt.Color("Author_Rating:N", 
                        legend=alt.Legend(title="Author_Rating", 
                                          titleFontWeight="bold"))  
    )
    .properties(
        width=700,
        height=400
    )
)

sale_price_chart = (
    alt.Chart(filtered_books)
    .transform_aggregate(
        avg_sale_price='mean(Sale_Price)', 
        groupby=["Publishing_Year", "Author_Rating"]
    )
    .mark_line()
    .encode(
        x=alt.X("Publishing_Year:O", 
                title="Publishing_Year",
                axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),  
        y=alt.Y("avg_sale_price:Q", 
                title="Average Sale Price",
                axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),  
        color=alt.Color("Author_Rating:N", 
                        legend=alt.Legend(title="Author_Rating", 
                                          titleFontWeight="bold"))  
    )
    .properties(
        width=700,
        height=400
    )
)

final_chart = alt.vconcat(revenue_chart, sale_price_chart).resolve_scale(
    y='shared'
).resolve_legend(
    color="shared" 
)

final_chart

alt.themes.register('my_theme', lambda: {
    "config": {
        "title": {"fontWeight": "bold"},      
        "axis": {"titleFontWeight": "bold"}      
    }
})
alt.themes.enable('my_theme')
alt.data_transformers.disable_max_rows()
book_data = book_data[book_data["Language_Code"].notnull()].copy()

english_books = book_data[
    book_data["Language_Code"].str.startswith("en-") | (book_data["Language_Code"] == "eng")
].copy()
non_english_books = book_data[
    ~(book_data["Language_Code"].str.startswith("en-") | (book_data["Language_Code"] == "eng"))
].copy()


english_mean_rating = english_books.groupby("Publisher")["Book_Average_Rating"].mean()
non_english_mean_rating = non_english_books.groupby("Publisher")["Book_Average_Rating"].mean()
combined_mean_rating = pd.concat([english_mean_rating, non_english_mean_rating])
rating_domain = [combined_mean_rating.min(), combined_mean_rating.max()]

english_mean_units = english_books.groupby("Publisher")["Units_Sold"].mean()
non_english_mean_units = non_english_books.groupby("Publisher")["Units_Sold"].mean()
combined_mean_units = pd.concat([english_mean_units, non_english_mean_units])
units_domain = [combined_mean_units.min(), combined_mean_units.max()]

chart_width = 220  
chart_height = 170  

english_rating_chart = alt.Chart(english_books).transform_aggregate(
    mean_rating='mean(Book_Average_Rating)', groupby=["Publisher"]).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X("mean_rating:Q", 
            title="Mean of Book_Average_Rating", 
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    y=alt.Y("Publisher:N", 
            title="Publisher",
            sort=alt.EncodingSortField(field="mean_rating", op="mean", order="descending"),
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    color=alt.Color("mean_rating:Q",
                    scale=alt.Scale(scheme="reds", domain=rating_domain),
                    legend=None)
).properties(
    title="English Language Books Average Ratings",
    width=chart_width,
    height=chart_height
)

non_english_rating_chart = alt.Chart(non_english_books).transform_aggregate(
    mean_rating='mean(Book_Average_Rating)', groupby=["Publisher"]).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X("mean_rating:Q", 
            title="Mean of Book_Average_Rating", 
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    y=alt.Y("Publisher:N", 
            title="Publisher",
            sort=alt.EncodingSortField(field="mean_rating", op="mean", order="descending"),
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    color=alt.Color("mean_rating:Q",
                    scale=alt.Scale(scheme="reds", domain=rating_domain),
                    legend=alt.Legend(title="Mean of Book_Average_Rating", titleFontWeight="bold"))
).properties(
    title="Other Language Books Average Ratings",
    width=chart_width,
    height=chart_height
)


ratings_row = alt.hconcat(english_rating_chart, non_english_rating_chart).resolve_scale(
    y='shared', color='independent'
)


english_units_chart = alt.Chart(english_books).transform_aggregate(
    mean_units='mean(Units_Sold)', groupby=["Publisher"]).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X("mean_units:Q", 
            title="Mean of Units_Sold", 
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    y=alt.Y("Publisher:N", 
            title="Publisher",
            sort=alt.EncodingSortField(field="mean_units", op="mean", order="descending"),
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    color=alt.Color("mean_units:Q",
                    scale=alt.Scale(scheme="blues", domain=units_domain),
                    legend=None)).properties(
    title="English Language Books Average Units Sold",
    width=chart_width,
    height=chart_height
)

non_english_units_chart = alt.Chart(non_english_books).transform_aggregate(
    mean_units='mean(Units_Sold)', groupby=["Publisher"]).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X("mean_units:Q", 
            title="Mean of Units_Sold", 
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    y=alt.Y("Publisher:N", 
            title="Publisher",
            sort=alt.EncodingSortField(field="mean_units", op="mean", order="descending"),
            axis=alt.Axis(titleFontWeight="bold")),
    color=alt.Color("mean_units:Q",
                    scale=alt.Scale(scheme="blues", domain=units_domain),
                    legend=alt.Legend(
                        title="Mean of Units_Sold", 
                        titleFontWeight="bold",
                        values=units_domain))).properties(
    title="Other Language Books Average Units Sold",
    width=chart_width,
    height=chart_height
)

units_row = alt.hconcat(english_units_chart, non_english_units_chart).resolve_scale(
    y='shared', color='independent'
)

final_chart = alt.vconcat(
    ratings_row,
    units_row
)

final_chart

book_data_filtered = book_data[book_data["Genre"] != "children"].copy()

bin_size = 200
book_data_filtered["Sale_Rank_binned"] = (
    book_data_filtered["Sale_Rank"] // bin_size
) * bin_size
book_data_filtered["Sale_Rank_binned_end"] = (
    book_data_filtered["Sale_Rank_binned"] + bin_size
)
book_data_filtered["Sale_Rank_bin_mid"] = (
    book_data_filtered["Sale_Rank_binned"] + bin_size / 2
)

agg_data = (
    book_data_filtered.groupby(["Genre", "Sale_Rank_binned"])
    .size()
    .reset_index(name="count_books")
)
agg_data["Sale_Rank_binned_end"] = agg_data["Sale_Rank_binned"] + bin_size
agg_data["Sale_Rank_bin_mid"] = agg_data["Sale_Rank_binned"] + bin_size / 2

heatmap = alt.Chart(agg_data).mark_rect().encode(
    x=alt.X(
        "Sale_Rank_binned:Q",
        title="Sale_Rank (binned)",
        scale=alt.Scale(domain=[0, 1400], padding=0),
        axis=alt.Axis(
            values=[0, 200, 400, 600, 800, 1000, 1200, 1400],
            labelAngle=0
        )
    ),
    x2=alt.X2("Sale_Rank_binned_end:Q"),
    y=alt.Y("Genre:N", title="Genre"),
    color=alt.Color(
        "count_books:Q",
        scale=alt.Scale(
            scheme="yellowgreen", 
            domain=[0, agg_data["count_books"].max()]
        ),
        title="Count of Records",
        legend=alt.Legend(
            orient="right",
            gradientLength=320,
            gradientThickness=20,
            labelExpr="datum.value === 0 ? '' : datum.value"
        )
    )
).properties(
    width=650,
    height=320
)

text = alt.Chart(agg_data).mark_text(
    baseline="middle",
    fontSize=14,
    fontWeight="bold",
    align="center",
    color="black"
).encode(
    x=alt.X("Sale_Rank_bin_mid:Q"),
    y=alt.Y("Genre:N"),
    text=alt.Text("count_books:Q")
)

final_heatmap = (heatmap + text).configure_axis(
    labelFontSize=12,
    titleFontSize=14,
    titleFontWeight="bold"  
).configure_legend(
    titleFontSize=12,
    titleFontWeight="bold",  
    labelFontSize=10
)

final_heatmap

Written Response: Chart Critique

These charts are a great start, but they are unpolished. If we wanted to publish these visualizations, we would need to make some changes. Choose one of the four charts and provide 3 suggestions on how you would improve the chart before publication.

Chart: [Visualization 3: Bar charts with average book rating and units sold by publisher for English language books versus other language books]

  1. Enhance color differentiation in the legend:

    Observing the English Language Books Average Ratings and English Language Books Average Units Sold plots, we can see that their x-values are relatively close, especially for the left top plot. This means that the color variations within each chart are subtle and do not provide a strong visual distinction between different publishers. Human perception of color differences is limited, especially when variations are small. Because of this, viewers may struggle to detect meaningful differences in the data trends.

    Suggestion: Expand the color domain in the legend, meaning the color mapping should have a wider range of shades, making it easier to distinguish high and low values. In this way, even though the x-values may be close, they have much more color difference than now. This will ensure that even minor differences in book ratings or sales become visually noticeable, improving the clarity of the charts.

  1. Increase the number of values in legend labels for better interpretation

    Currently the legend provides very few labeled values (the red one has only three divisions and the blue one only has the max and min values). This gives readers insufficient guidance on what each color represents. If there are too few labels in the legend, readers have to guess the meaning of intermediate colors, reducing the accuracy of interpretation. This can lead to misunderstandings, as users may not correctly estimate the values associated with certain shades.

    Suggestion:Add more intervals in the legend (for example use 5 intervals in this conidtion). This will help viewers more accurately map colors to their respective values. Each color step should be clearly marked with a numerical value so that readers dont have to estimate or assume values based on color gradients alone.

  1. Include a large title to provide context for all 4 charts

    Each chart currently has its own individual title, which describes what the chart represents, but there is no overall title for the entire visualization. This makes it difficult for viewers to understand the broader context without first examining all four charts separately. Also, as the multiple charts are shown together, they are usually produced to present a comparative analysis. Without a large overarching title, viewers may not immediately realize that the charts are meant to be compared (e.g., English vs. other language books). Moreover, there is so much information in the plots; if there is not a whole title, it really costs the reader time to explore what it is about.

    Suggested Improvement: Add a bold and big title at the top and in the middle of the visualization. For example, the title could be "Comparison of Book Ratings and Sales by Publisher between English and Other Languages." In this way, it will immediately inform the audience that these charts are meant to compare ratings and sales performance across different language categories, making the purpose of the visualization clearer.
